In Parts 1–3, we built the foundation: model setup, data flow, and validation across Template-driven, Reactive, and Signal Forms. In this final part, we tackle the patterns that show up in production.
📚 This article is Part 4 of a series on Angular Forms. Start from Part 1 to understand where the form model lives and how it binds to the UI.
Angular Forms — Model Setup and UI Binding (Part 1) 🔥🚀

🧪 All examples in this article are available in an interactive StackBlitz playground, where you can explore dynamic fields, async validation, and custom controls hands-on.
⚡ StackBlitz project — Part 4

Signal Forms are stable in Angular v22. That changes things. For the first time in this series, the experimental warning comes off.
This is the article where the full picture clicks into place.
To keep things realistic, we graduate from the simple login form we used in Parts 1–3. This part introduces a registration form — a more natural domain for dynamic fields, async validation, and custom controls.
⚡ A Quick Note on Angular v22
Starting from v22, Signal Forms ship as a stable API. The @angular/forms/signals package is no longer experimental. You can use it in production without bracing for breaking changes.
If you have existing articles or codebases carrying the experimental disclaimer, now is the time to update them.
💡 Signal Forms are not a drop-in replacement for Reactive or Template-driven Forms. They are a rethought-from-scratch implementation. The core concepts — validation state, touched, dirty, pending — remain familiar. The API is different by design.

🧱 Baseline: The Registration Form
Throughout this article we use the same domain: a registration form with a username, an email, a password, and a dynamic list of phone numbers. The model stays consistent across sections so the differences between approaches stay the focus.
Here is the minimal setup for each, without validation or dynamic fields yet — those come in the next sections.
Template-driven
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormsModule, NgForm } from '@angular/forms';@Component({
selector: 'app-registration',
imports: [FormsModule],
template: `
<form #f="ngForm" (ngSubmit)="submit(f)">
<input name="username" [(ngModel)]="model.username" />
<input name="email" [(ngModel)]="model.email" />
<input name="password" type="password" [(ngModel)]="model.password" />
<button type="submit">Register</button>
</form>
`
})
export class RegistrationComponent {
model = { username: '', email: '', password: '' };
submit(form: NgForm): void {
console.log(form.value);
}
}
Reactive
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormGroup, FormControl, Validators, ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';@Component({
selector: 'app-registration',
imports: [ReactiveFormsModule],
template: `
<form [formGroup]="form" (ngSubmit)="submit()">
<input formControlName="username" />
<input formControlName="email" />
<input formControlName="password" type="password" />
<button type="submit">Register</button>
</form>
`
})
export class RegistrationComponent {
form = new FormGroup({
username: new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true, validators: [Validators.required] }),
email: new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true, validators: [Validators.required, Validators.email] }),
password: new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true, validators: [Validators.required, Validators.minLength(8)] }),
});
submit(): void {
console.log(this.form.value);
}
}
Signal Forms
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { form, FormField, required, email, minLength } from '@angular/forms/signals';@Component({
selector: 'app-registration',
imports: [FormField],
template: `
<form (ngSubmit)="submit()">
<input [formField]="f.username" />
<input [formField]="f.email" />
<input [formField]="f.password" type="password" />
<button type="submit">Register</button>
</form>
`
})
export class RegistrationComponent {
model = signal({ username: '', email: '', password: '' });
f = form(this.model, (path) => {
required(path.username);
required(path.email);
email(path.email);
required(path.password);
minLength(path.password, 8);
});
submit(): void {
console.log(this.model());
}
}

🔁 Dynamic Forms
Real applications rarely have a fixed number of fields. A form that lets users add multiple phone numbers, skills, or shipping addresses is a common scenario. This is where the three approaches diverge most visibly.
Template-driven: plain array with @for
Template-driven Forms have no built-in construct for managing dynamic arrays. The standard approach is to keep a plain array in the component and iterate over it with Angular’s @for block.
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';@Component({
selector: 'app-phone-list',
imports: [FormsModule],
template: `
@for (phone of phones; track $index) {
<div>
<input [name]="'phone_' + $index" [(ngModel)]="phones[$index]" />
<button type="button" (click)="remove($index)">Remove</button>
</div>
}
<button type="button" (click)="add()">Add phone</button>
`
})
export class PhoneListComponent {
phones: string[] = [''];
add(): void {
this.phones.push('');
}
remove(index: number): void {
this.phones.splice(index, 1);
}
}
This works for simple cases, but Angular has no awareness of the array as a unit. There is no aggregate validity, no array-level validators, and no clean way to reset the entire list programmatically.
Reactive: FormArray
Reactive Forms provide FormArray, a first-class construct for managing a dynamic list of controls. Each item is a full FormControl, which means it participates in validation, state tracking, and the overall form validity.
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { FormArray, FormControl, FormGroup, ReactiveFormsModule, Validators } from '@angular/forms';@Component({
selector: 'app-phone-list',
imports: [ReactiveFormsModule],
template: `
<form [formGroup]="form">
<div formArrayName="phones">
@for (ctrl of phones.controls; track $index) {
<div>
<input [formControlName]="$index" />
@if (ctrl.invalid && ctrl.touched) {
<span>Phone number is required.</span>
}
<button type="button" (click)="remove($index)">Remove</button>
</div>
}
</div>
<button type="button" (click)="add()">Add phone</button>
</form>
`
})
export class PhoneListComponent {
form = new FormGroup({
phones: new FormArray([
new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true, validators: [Validators.required] })
])
});
get phones(): FormArray {
return this.form.controls.phones;
}
add(): void {
this.phones.push(
new FormControl('', { nonNullable: true, validators: [Validators.required] })
);
}
remove(index: number): void {
this.phones.removeAt(index);
}
}
The array is a first-class citizen. this.phones.valid reflects the validity of all items at once. Adding and removing controls is explicit and synchronous.
The cost is verbosity: every add() call must manually instantiate a control and re-wire its validators. The logic lives in the component, not in the schema.
Signal Forms: model-driven arrays with applyEach()
Signal Forms take a different approach entirely. There is no FormArray class to instantiate. Dynamic fields are just arrays in your model signal. When you push or splice that array, the form reacts automatically.
Schema rules for each item are declared once using applyEach(). They apply to every element, including items added after form creation.
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { form, FormField, applyEach, required } from '@angular/forms/signals';interface RegistrationModel {
username: string;
phones: string[];
}
@Component({
selector: 'app-phone-list',
imports: [FormField],
template: `
@for (phone of f.phones; track $index) {
<div>
<input [formField]="phone" />
@if (phone().invalid() && phone().touched()) {
<span>Phone number is required.</span>
}
<button type="button" (click)="remove($index)">Remove</button>
</div>
}
<button type="button" (click)="add()">Add phone</button>
`
})
export class PhoneListComponent {
model = signal<RegistrationModel>({ username: '', phones: [''] });
f = form(this.model, (path) => {
applyEach(path.phones, (phone) => {
required(phone);
});
});
add(): void {
this.model.update(m => ({ ...m, phones: [...m.phones, ''] }));
}
remove(index: number): void {
this.model.update(m => ({
...m,
phones: m.phones.filter((_, i) => i !== index)
}));
}
}
No class to instantiate per item. No manual validator wiring on each add. You update the model signal, and the form structure catches up automatically.
💡 The key insight In Signal Forms, the model signal is the source of truth not a parallel data structure you maintain alongside it. This is what “model-driven” actually means in practice.

⏳ Async Validation
Some validation rules cannot run on the client alone. Checking whether a username is already taken, verifying a tax ID, or validating a coupon code all require a server round-trip.
Angular supports async validators across all three approaches, but the ergonomics differ significantly.
A note on structure
In the examples below, the validator logic is kept separate from the display component. This is intentional. The component renders the form; the validator enforces a rule. They are two different responsibilities, and keeping them separate makes both easier to test.
Template-driven: custom async directive
Template-driven Forms have no built-in async validator API. You create a directive that implements AsyncValidator and registers itself via NG_ASYNC_VALIDATORS.
import { Directive, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { AbstractControl, AsyncValidator, NG_ASYNC_VALIDATORS, ValidationErrors } from '@angular/forms';
import { Observable, of, timer, switchMap, map, catchError } from 'rxjs';
import { UserService } from './user.service';@Directive({
selector: '[uniqueUsername]',
providers: [
{
provide: NG_ASYNC_VALIDATORS,
useExisting: UniqueUsernameDirective,
multi: true
}
]
})
export class UniqueUsernameDirective implements AsyncValidator {
private userService = inject(UserService);
validate(control: AbstractControl): Observable<ValidationErrors | null> {
if (!control.value) return of(null);
return timer(400).pipe(
switchMap(() => this.userService.checkUsername(control.value)),
map(isTaken => isTaken ? { usernameTaken: true } : null),
catchError(() => of(null))
);
}
}
The directive is applied as an attribute on the input, and Angular picks it up through the NG_ASYNC_VALIDATORS token:
<input name="username" [(ngModel)]="model.username" uniqueUsername />The pending state is accessible via the #ngModel template reference, but reading and displaying it in the template requires extra ceremony compared to Reactive Forms.
Reactive: asyncValidators option
Reactive Forms accept async validators directly on a control, alongside sync validators. The control enters pending state while the validator runs — the same pending state you saw in Part 3.
The validator is a standalone factory function. The component wires it in:
// unique-username.validator.ts
import { AbstractControl, ValidationErrors } from '@angular/forms';
import { Observable, of, timer, switchMap, map, catchError } from 'rxjs';
import { UserService } from './user.service';export function uniqueUsernameValidator(userService: UserService) {
return (control: AbstractControl): Observable<ValidationErrors | null> => {
if (!control.value) return of(null);
return timer(400).pipe(
switchMap(() => userService.checkUsername(control.value)),
map(isTaken => isTaken ? { usernameTaken: true } : null),
catchError(() => of(null))
);
};
}
// registration.component.ts
import { Component, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { FormControl, ReactiveFormsModule, Validators } from '@angular/forms';
import { UserService } from './user.service';
import { uniqueUsernameValidator } from './unique-username.validator';@Component({
